Task set 1: RECAP

  1. Load the required libraries of tidyverse and gapminder using the library() function.
  1. The chunk below contains part of the code required to create a scatter plot. Complete it to create a scatter plot showing the relationship between population and gddPercap for latest year for every country
gapminder %>% 
    group_by(country) %>% 
    filter(year == max(year, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = pop, y = gdpPercap)) +
    geom_point()

  1. The previous scatter looks weird because there are a few population values that are really big that elongate the x-axis while most of the variation in the data happens on the left-side of this axis. The same things is happening on the y-axis. We can compress this chart by taking logs. A Log transformation is useful to highlight underlying patterns in highly skewed data (long tails). Set the x aesthetic as log(pop) instead of pop and log(gdpPercap) instead of gdpPercap for the y-aesthetic. Like so mapping = aes(x = log(pop), y = log(gdpPercap)).
gapminder %>% 
    group_by(country) %>% 
    filter(year == max(year, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = log(pop), y = log(gdpPercap))) +
    geom_point()

  1. Now that we have a scatter plot that highlights the relationship between the two variables lets adding a line that characterizes this relationship. You can do this by adding geom_smooth(method = "lm") to your code. Bonus task: Change the colour of the confidence bands around the line to red and set its opacity (using alpha aesthetic) to 1.
gapminder %>% 
    group_by(country) %>% 
    filter(year == max(year, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = log(pop), y = log(gdpPercap))) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method='lm', color = 'red', alpha = 1)

  1. Now lets map an additional aesthetic. Inside the aesthetic mapping in the ggplot() function, set the colour of the dots to the continent.
gapminder %>% 
    group_by(country) %>% 
    filter(year == max(year, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = log(pop), y = log(gdpPercap), color = continent)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method='lm', color = 'red', alpha = 1)

  1. Finally lets also facet this plot by the continent. Use facet_wrap(~continent, nrow = 1) to facet this plot by continent
gapminder %>% 
    group_by(country) %>% 
    filter(year == max(year, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = log(pop), y = log(gdpPercap), color = continent)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method='lm') +
    facet_wrap(~continent, nrow = 1)

  1. Hard: Extend the chart above by adding labels using geom_label() indicating the names of the countries that have gdpPercap above 35000 USD. Hint: You will need to save the data separately and set it within different geoms differently.
plotData <- gapminder %>% 
    group_by(country) %>% 
    filter(year == max(year, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ungroup()
ggplot(data = plotData, mapping = aes(x = log(pop), y = log(gdpPercap), color = continent)) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm', color = 'red', alpha = 1) +
    geom_label(data = plotData %>% 
                 filter(gdpPercap > 35000),
                 aes(label = country)) +
    geom_point() +
    facet_wrap(~continent, nrow = 1)

  1. Legendary: Look up the ggrepel package and use geom_label_repel() from it instead of the geom_label().

Task Set 2: Make an aesthetically appealing chart

  1. The code chunk below creates a multiline chart using the flights dataset that we are familiar with. Each line indicates an origin airport. Create a similar chart using the gapminder dataset that shows the trends in average yearly gdpPercap for each continent. The final chart should have one line with the dots for each continent showing the trend in gdpPercap over time.
library(nycflights13)
flights %>%
    group_by(hour, origin) %>%
    summarise(meanDelay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = T)) %>%
    ungroup() %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = hour, y = meanDelay, colour = origin)) +
    geom_line(na.rm = T) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.5, size = 2.5, na.rm = T) +
    labs(
        x = "Hour of departure",
        y = "Mean departure delay (in minutes)",
        title = "Avoid evening flights out of NYC if possible"
        ) +
    theme_minimal()

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent, year) %>%
  summarize(meanGdpPercap = mean(gdpPercap, na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = meanGdpPercap, color = continent)) +
  geom_line(na.rm = T) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, size = 2.5, na.rm = T) +
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Mean GDP Growth Per Capita",
       title = "Wealth grows wealth") +
  theme_minimal()
ggsave('wealth_over_time.png')
